<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06066210 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06066210 </ACCESS><CAPTION>  Drawing; DRAWING: Jim Hummel. (Souffle)  </CAPTION><DESCRIPT>  FOOD; RECIPE  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  DON'T be surprised if you grow so fond of leftovers that you buy a leg of lambjust so you can use it in a leftover version of lamb curry.;    LAMB CURRY  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Food  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  MAIN DISHES THAT FILL THE ENTREE BILL EVENBETTER THE SECOND TIME AROUND  </HEADLINE><MEMO>  See also related article on page 1E of this section.  </MEMO><TEXT>  2  tablespoons butter;  3/4 cup chopped onions; 2 tablespoons curry powder; 2tablespoons chopped crystallized ginger; 1 14-ounce can coconut milk; 1 1/2pounds cooked lamb, cut in 3/4-inch cubes; 1 cup cubed, ripe but firm fruitsuch as papaya, mango, banana or pineapple (optional);  Salt and pepper totaste; 3 cups cooked basmati rice;  Grated coconut or fresh chopped mint(optional);   Heat butter in a deep skillet and saute onions untiltranslucent. Add curry and cook a few minutes over low heat, stirring. Addginger, coconut milk and lamb. Bring to a simmer and let thicken. Add fruit ifdesired and cook until heated through. Season to taste with salt and pepper.Serve over basmati rice garnished with grated coconut or fresh mint. Serves4.; (hbox);    WARM MARINATED PORK SALAD; 3  tablespoons each, soy sauce,walnut oil and dry white wine; 1 teaspoon fresh rosemary leaves or 1/3teaspoon dried; 1 garlic clove, put through a press; 1 1/2 pounds leftoverpork roast or chops;  3/4 pound green beans;  About 2 large heads butter orBoston lettuce; 2 4-ounce jars sliced pimentos; 2 tablespoons peanut oil; 31/2 tablespoons balsamic or red wine vinegar;  Salt and pepper to taste; 1medium garlic clove, put through a press;  1/2 cup walnut oil; 1 cup toastedwalnuts; 6 ounces Gorgonzola or other blue cheese;   Combine soy sauce, walnutoil, wine, rosemary and garlic in a bowl. Slice pork in 2-inch long stripsabout 1/4-inch thick and 1/2-inch wide. Add to soy sauce mixture, toss andmarinate 30 minutes to 1 hour at room temperature. Cook green beans in agenerous amount of boiling, salted water about 5 minutes or until just tender.Drain and refresh in cold or ice water. Clean lettuce and tear into bite-sizepieces. Drain pimentos.;    Heat peanut oil in a heavy skillet until oilsmokes. Remove pork from marinade, reserve marinade and add pork to skillet.Cook, stirring, over high heat until just heated through, about 2 minutes. Setskillet aside. Strain marinade into a saucepan and simmer 5 minutes. Setaside.;    To assemble salad, mix vinegar, salt, pepper and garlic with walnutoil and reserved marinade. Put lettuce in the bottom of a large bowl (a wide,shallow one works best). Top with green beans, pimentos, walnuts and crumbledblue cheese. Pour dressing over and toss. Serves 6. (Adapted from &quot;Good andamp;Plenty&quot; Victoria Wise and Susanna Hoffman, Harper andamp; Row, $22.95).; (hbox);   The following two recipes were adapted from &quot;The Fanny Farmer Cookbook&quot; byMarion Cunningham (Alfred A. Knopf, $24.95). Use the souffle recipe for anyleftover vegetable.;    SALMON CAKES; 1  pound leftover poached salmon, bonesremoved;  3/4 cup fresh bread crumbs;  1/4 cup minced scallions; 2 tablespoonschopped parsley; 2 tablespoons chopped dill;  1/4 cup leftover hollandaise (ormayonnaise); 2 tablespoons milk; 1 egg;  Salt, black pepper and cayenne pepperto taste;  Lemon wedges;   Put fish in a bowl and flake with a fork. Add breadcrumbs, scallions, parsley, dill and hollandaise and mix. Beat milk and eggand add to the fish mixture. Season to taste with salt, pepper and cayenne.Form into slightly oval patties about 3/4-inch thick. Cook, covered, 5-8minutes on high in a microwave oven. Serve with lemon wedges.; (hbox);   BROCCOLI SOUFFLE; 4  tablespoons butter;  1/4 cup flour; 1 1/4 cups milk; Salt to taste;  Freshly grated nutmeg to taste;  1/2 cup grated Parmesan orCheddar cheese; 4 eggs, well beaten; 2 cups pureed leftover broccoli;  Preheat oven to 375. Butter a 1-quart oven-proof dish and place in a pancontaining 1 inch of hot water. Melt butter in a saucepan. Stir in flour andblend until smooth. Cook 2-3 minutes over low heat. Slowly add milk and cook,stirring constantly, 3 minutes or until smooth and thick. Add salt, gratednutmeg and cheese and blend well until cheese melts. Remove from heat. Beat 3tablespoons sauce into eggs, then return egg-sauce mixture to saucepan andbeat until smooth. Fold in broccoli puree. Pour into baking dish and bakeuntil lightly brown and set, 25-30 minutes.; (hbox);    ROAST BEEF HASH; 3 tablespoons oil; 2 cups chopped onions; 3 cloves garlic, chopped; 2 cupscooked potatoes, cut into 1/2- to 3/4-inch cubes; 2 cups leftover roast beef,cut into 1/2-inch cubes; 1 teaspoon each, dried thyme and sage;  Tabasco totaste;  Salt and pepper to taste;  1/3 cup heavy cream; 4 eggs;   In a large,heavy skillet, heat oil over moderate heat and gently saute onions untiltranslucent. Add garlic, cook a few minutes more. Add potatoes and mix well.Add beef and seasonings and mix well. Press mixture down with a spatula into alarge pancake. Drizzle cream over and press down again. Cook about 20-30minutes until hash has a golden crust on the bottom. Mark top of the hash intofour sections and break an egg in each section. Cover and cook about fiveminutes or until eggs are just cooked. Serve a wedge of hash with an egg ontop to each person. Serves 4.; -- Adapted from &quot;Leftovers&quot;  </TEXT><BYLINE>  SAM GUGINO, Mercury News Food Editor  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><EDITION>  Morning Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910306  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Wednesday  </DAY><MONTH>  March  </MONTH><PG.COL>  5E  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><FEATURE>  DRAWING  </FEATURE><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  906  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Wednesday March 6, 199100066210,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copy